1
00:00:00,160 --> 00:00:05,480
Okay guys, welcome back to Gary's Economics. This week we've got something a little bit different for you.

2
00:00:05,620 --> 00:00:13,120
We are going to show you a live recording of a speech I gave at Cambridge to kick off my book launch a couple of months ago.

3
00:00:14,800 --> 00:00:20,160
I've got to be honest, if we've gotten around to this point, it means basically we have run out of videos.

4
00:00:20,900 --> 00:00:26,700
And the reason for that is because I am currently on holiday cycling from Tokyo to Kagoshima in southwestern Japan.

5
00:00:26,700 --> 00:00:33,660
All right. Listen, it's been a pretty mental year for me. I've been working really hard. The channel has grown a lot.

6
00:00:34,879 --> 00:00:40,960
I've had a ton of publicity with the book. Trying to grow everything, trying to push things politically and it's been a lot of work.

7
00:00:41,300 --> 00:00:50,300
And to be honest, I'm feeling a little bit creatively exhausted and, you know, we get a lot of support for this channel now.

8
00:00:50,300 --> 00:00:55,580
I've got a manager and we've got Jack here, the videographer, but creatively it's still basically me who does the videos.

9
00:00:55,580 --> 00:01:03,580
And with all the book and the interviews and the videos for the channel, I'm feeling a bit knackered and the election, all that nonsense.

10
00:01:04,379 --> 00:01:06,679
So I've decided to get out of here, go back to Japan.

11
00:01:07,880 --> 00:01:12,440
Those of you who have read the book when I lived in Japan for two years and I used to spend a lot of time in there before COVID.

12
00:01:12,440 --> 00:01:19,660
So I've decided to take a little bit of a break, go and do this cycle that I've wanted to do for ages from Tokyo to to southwest Japan.

13
00:01:20,039 --> 00:01:26,039
And I've tried my best to film videos to fill the gap, but I'm not sure we're going to be able to cover the whole time.

14
00:01:26,280 --> 00:01:34,640
And we've scheduled this to be the last video before we go blank for a bit, maybe for part of August, before I come back for my holiday.

15
00:01:34,640 --> 00:01:39,960
And this is a speech I gave at Robinson College in Cambridge.

16
00:01:41,400 --> 00:01:44,800
It's a little bit more personal, a little bit more emotional than a lot of the stuff that I do.

17
00:01:45,040 --> 00:01:52,160
Talking about sort of how I deal with sort of living in this economy where things get worse and worse and trying to stop it.

18
00:01:52,160 --> 00:02:00,539
I think it's a really nice speech and I promised a room full of Scousers in Waterstones, Liverpool that I'd put it up on the YouTube at some point.

19
00:02:00,660 --> 00:02:01,800
So hopefully they're still watching.

20
00:02:03,039 --> 00:02:09,620
Unfortunately, there's a few problems with the sound quality, but since we've got a gap with no videos, I think it's worth watching.

21
00:02:09,699 --> 00:02:11,680
I think it's really interesting. It's about 45 minutes long.

22
00:02:12,440 --> 00:02:15,560
I hope you like it. I get a little bit emotional in it.

23
00:02:15,560 --> 00:02:22,840
But after this, I think we'll probably have a gap of a few weeks before I come back in September and start shooting again.

24
00:02:23,880 --> 00:02:26,580
So this will be it for me for a few weeks.

25
00:02:29,480 --> 00:02:32,420
I'll be back and I hope you enjoy this last video. Thank you.

26
00:02:32,880 --> 00:02:35,440
And also thanks for all of your help this year.

27
00:02:35,540 --> 00:02:41,060
The growth has been really good and been really mental and hopefully we'll be able to have a little bit more political impact when I come back.

28
00:02:41,440 --> 00:02:41,860
Thank you.

29
00:02:41,860 --> 00:02:54,880
When I was contacted to do this lecture, they said, come to Robertson College, talk about economics, tell everyone why inequality is a problem.

30
00:02:56,260 --> 00:02:59,680
And my agent said, that's perfect timing for your book launch, go do it.

31
00:03:02,740 --> 00:03:05,860
So I said yes, and that's about a year ago now.

32
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:08,460
I didn't really think about it much.

33
00:03:08,460 --> 00:03:16,780
Then they reached out to me a couple of months ago and they said, what do you want the title of your lecture to be?

34
00:03:18,120 --> 00:03:26,800
And my first thought when they said that was, I don't really want to talk about economics anymore.

35
00:03:29,960 --> 00:03:31,060
Let me explain to you why.

36
00:03:31,060 --> 00:03:33,880
I've been talking about economics for a long time now.

37
00:03:35,020 --> 00:03:42,800
13 years, 14 years, I've been having arguments about economics, trying to tell people inequality is a problem, inequality is a problem.

38
00:03:43,780 --> 00:03:46,100
It's going to get worse, it's going to get worse, we need to do something.

39
00:03:46,100 --> 00:04:02,340
And over the course of those 14 years, especially in the last year or two, what I've noticed is the arguments I've been having have been changing.

40
00:04:02,340 --> 00:04:10,680
And more and more I start to think to myself that actually, we're not really arguing about economics at all.

41
00:04:10,680 --> 00:04:21,019
See, when I first started saying inequality was a problem, I was working in a bank in Canary Wharf in London, and I was surrounded by millionaires of economics degrees.

42
00:04:21,019 --> 00:04:29,859
And they would say to me, you can't tax wealth, you can't deal with inequality, because we need the rich to invest, to grow the economy.

43
00:04:30,520 --> 00:04:36,200
The optimal rate of taxation in the first best of all possible worlds on capital is zero.

44
00:04:38,979 --> 00:04:40,760
But nobody really says that to me anymore.

45
00:04:42,140 --> 00:04:50,760
Okay, some people do say that sometimes in places like this, people say that, but nobody with that fancy economics degree says that to me anymore.

46
00:04:51,020 --> 00:05:00,280
What people say to me now is, you can't tax the rich, you can't tax, they're too powerful.

47
00:05:01,320 --> 00:05:04,659
You tax the rich, they'll leave and they'll go away and then we'll have nothing and then we'll be poor.

48
00:05:06,359 --> 00:05:11,299
Or they say to me, it's impossible trying to deal with inequality.

49
00:05:12,599 --> 00:05:15,840
Inequality is just the way things are, the rich are too powerful.

50
00:05:16,859 --> 00:05:18,640
Why are you trying to stop them? You're wasting your time.

51
00:05:18,640 --> 00:05:24,539
Or they say to me, why are you trying to stop inequality?

52
00:05:25,599 --> 00:05:29,060
Why don't you just trade Bitcoin or foreign exchange on the internet?

53
00:05:29,760 --> 00:05:31,240
That's the way to make everything better.

54
00:05:33,700 --> 00:05:35,120
Or they say to me,

55
00:05:35,120 --> 00:05:44,220
You know, the economy and society, it's like the cycles of nature.

56
00:05:45,160 --> 00:05:48,040
Sometimes it's good and sometimes it's bad.

57
00:05:48,660 --> 00:05:51,180
Sometimes it gets better and sometimes it gets worse.

58
00:05:52,200 --> 00:05:53,680
So why are you trying to change things?

59
00:05:54,660 --> 00:05:56,540
You can't fight the cycles of nature.

60
00:05:56,540 --> 00:06:02,580
And the more I heard these arguments, the more I started to think,

61
00:06:03,320 --> 00:06:06,460
we're not really arguing about the economy.

62
00:06:08,140 --> 00:06:11,260
Increasingly, everybody knows it's getting worse and worse.

63
00:06:12,840 --> 00:06:16,720
Really, hardly any real people think it's going to get better.

64
00:06:16,720 --> 00:06:20,900
But I think people in their heart of hearts realise

65
00:06:20,900 --> 00:06:24,880
that it just gets worse and worse from here.

66
00:06:25,760 --> 00:06:27,240
And when they're saying to me,

67
00:06:27,880 --> 00:06:30,160
why are you trying to fix things?

68
00:06:31,040 --> 00:06:32,740
Often they're really saying to themselves,

69
00:06:33,340 --> 00:06:35,520
I don't want to have to try to fix things.

70
00:06:35,520 --> 00:06:39,940
And I started to feel like the real questions

71
00:06:39,940 --> 00:06:41,900
that we're asking ourselves and each other

72
00:06:41,900 --> 00:06:43,740
is not really,

73
00:06:44,159 --> 00:06:45,640
is the economy broken?

74
00:06:48,299 --> 00:06:49,419
It's what do you do?

75
00:06:51,400 --> 00:06:54,039
What do you do when you live in a collapsing economy?

76
00:06:56,359 --> 00:06:57,419
What do you do?

77
00:06:58,260 --> 00:06:59,479
What should you do?

78
00:07:00,380 --> 00:07:02,400
And what does it mean?

79
00:07:03,740 --> 00:07:04,280
And more and more,

80
00:07:04,280 --> 00:07:05,900
these are the questions that I hear

81
00:07:05,900 --> 00:07:08,000
when I argue people about economics.

82
00:07:09,640 --> 00:07:10,660
What do you do?

83
00:07:11,360 --> 00:07:12,460
What should you do?

84
00:07:13,600 --> 00:07:14,820
What does it mean?

85
00:07:17,340 --> 00:07:19,700
And it got me thinking about my journey in economics.

86
00:07:21,040 --> 00:07:22,660
I've been an economist for,

87
00:07:23,580 --> 00:07:24,900
God, nearly 20 years now.

88
00:07:25,720 --> 00:07:27,660
But I lived in an economy my whole life.

89
00:07:29,080 --> 00:07:30,280
I grew up very poor,

90
00:07:30,400 --> 00:07:32,520
so really poverty and a collapsing economy

91
00:07:32,520 --> 00:07:33,340
is not new to me.

92
00:07:34,280 --> 00:07:36,320
But it got me thinking,

93
00:07:36,780 --> 00:07:38,980
what did I do?

94
00:07:40,500 --> 00:07:41,920
What should I have done differently?

95
00:07:43,240 --> 00:07:44,320
What does it all mean?

96
00:07:44,320 --> 00:07:49,420
So I sent a memo back saying I wanted to talk about

97
00:07:49,420 --> 00:07:51,340
what it means to be human in a collapsing economy.

98
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:53,659
And I'm going to talk a little bit about

99
00:07:53,659 --> 00:07:56,580
what I think about my path.

100
00:07:57,860 --> 00:08:00,700
And when I talk about that,

101
00:08:00,960 --> 00:08:04,659
I want you to think about those three main questions.

102
00:08:04,660 --> 00:08:08,300
What does it mean to live in a collapsing economy?

103
00:08:09,580 --> 00:08:11,760
What do you do when the economy is collapsing?

104
00:08:13,480 --> 00:08:14,440
And what should you do?

105
00:08:15,620 --> 00:08:17,840
And I'm going to stop at points and I'm going to ask those questions.

106
00:08:17,920 --> 00:08:18,420
And when I do that,

107
00:08:18,480 --> 00:08:19,320
I would like you to think,

108
00:08:19,320 --> 00:08:20,880
what would I do if that was me?

109
00:08:20,880 --> 00:08:24,500
And with regards to the second of those questions,

110
00:08:24,600 --> 00:08:26,140
what do you do when the economy is collapsing?

111
00:08:26,920 --> 00:08:28,480
All of you will have a perspective on that

112
00:08:28,480 --> 00:08:30,040
because you all live in a collapsing economy

113
00:08:30,040 --> 00:08:31,300
and you're all doing something.

114
00:08:32,860 --> 00:08:34,659
But this kind of economic collapse,

115
00:08:34,740 --> 00:08:35,500
which is in my opinion,

116
00:08:35,580 --> 00:08:36,679
a collapse caused by inequality,

117
00:08:37,380 --> 00:08:39,460
it's a collapse which looks very, very different

118
00:08:39,460 --> 00:08:42,039
depending on which angle you view it from.

119
00:08:42,039 --> 00:08:45,839
So some of you will have been in the situations I've been in

120
00:08:45,839 --> 00:08:46,699
and some of you won't have been.

121
00:08:48,280 --> 00:08:49,819
But I want you to take it as an opportunity

122
00:08:49,819 --> 00:08:52,219
to imagine you're in a different seat to where you are now

123
00:08:52,219 --> 00:08:55,439
and ask yourself, honestly, what would I do if that was me?

124
00:08:57,020 --> 00:08:58,500
Okay, so with that, I'm going to start,

125
00:08:59,160 --> 00:09:00,740
I don't really like reading from speeches,

126
00:09:00,900 --> 00:09:01,920
but I've written a little story.

127
00:09:03,540 --> 00:09:04,280
When I was writing,

128
00:09:04,360 --> 00:09:07,500
I wanted to start with my period of poverty,

129
00:09:07,959 --> 00:09:09,360
which lasted about 20 years.

130
00:09:10,160 --> 00:09:13,040
And I wrote a little bit about Ilford,

131
00:09:13,300 --> 00:09:13,940
which is my hometown,

132
00:09:14,200 --> 00:09:16,380
so I'm going to read it to you.

133
00:09:18,120 --> 00:09:19,540
I'm going to have to change this first line

134
00:09:19,540 --> 00:09:20,620
because there's a swear word in it.

135
00:09:23,540 --> 00:09:24,480
I grew up in Ilford.

136
00:09:25,980 --> 00:09:26,980
It's a bit of a slum,

137
00:09:28,200 --> 00:09:28,960
but it's my slum.

138
00:09:30,820 --> 00:09:34,100
Ilford is kind of a contested borderland war zone

139
00:09:34,100 --> 00:09:35,540
between East London and Essex.

140
00:09:35,540 --> 00:09:40,579
Everyone is from Pakistan or India or Sri Lanka or something,

141
00:09:41,579 --> 00:09:43,360
but everyone talks in a half-Cockney accent.

142
00:09:44,939 --> 00:09:46,199
When I was a teenager,

143
00:09:46,660 --> 00:09:48,540
I used to sing songs in Punjabi

144
00:09:48,540 --> 00:09:51,079
for illegal immigrants working in halal fried chicken shops

145
00:09:51,079 --> 00:09:52,180
at 2am in the morning

146
00:09:52,180 --> 00:09:53,580
for free chicken.

147
00:09:56,460 --> 00:09:57,580
What do you want me to tell you?

148
00:09:58,620 --> 00:09:59,420
I loved it.

149
00:10:00,720 --> 00:10:01,540
I still do.

150
00:10:02,440 --> 00:10:03,140
I miss it.

151
00:10:05,220 --> 00:10:07,720
Ilford is one of the cheapest places to live in all of London.

152
00:10:07,720 --> 00:10:11,560
I used to live in this tiny, narrow terraced house

153
00:10:11,560 --> 00:10:14,160
on a street full of tiny, narrow terraced houses,

154
00:10:14,940 --> 00:10:16,120
tucked in behind the high street.

155
00:10:17,120 --> 00:10:18,740
It had three bedrooms.

156
00:10:19,820 --> 00:10:21,200
It used to have two bedrooms,

157
00:10:21,620 --> 00:10:23,280
but somebody had moved the bathroom

158
00:10:23,280 --> 00:10:24,840
downstairs into the kitchen,

159
00:10:25,300 --> 00:10:27,020
which meant that they could turn the old bathroom

160
00:10:27,020 --> 00:10:28,800
upstairs into another bedroom.

161
00:10:28,800 --> 00:10:31,100
And that's where I grew up,

162
00:10:31,640 --> 00:10:33,140
in a bunk bed with my brother,

163
00:10:34,020 --> 00:10:36,700
in a bunk bed in an old converted bathroom.

164
00:10:38,620 --> 00:10:41,720
The train tracks that carried brokers and traders

165
00:10:41,720 --> 00:10:44,220
in fast trains from out in Essex

166
00:10:44,220 --> 00:10:45,540
down into the city

167
00:10:45,540 --> 00:10:47,680
used to run right through my garden,

168
00:10:48,360 --> 00:10:49,740
right past my bedroom window.

169
00:10:50,880 --> 00:10:52,440
And when the fast trains came through,

170
00:10:53,020 --> 00:10:54,440
the whole house used to shake.

171
00:10:54,440 --> 00:10:57,580
But I never noticed.

172
00:10:58,880 --> 00:11:00,300
When you grow up in a house

173
00:11:00,300 --> 00:11:02,180
that gets shaken by a fast train

174
00:11:02,180 --> 00:11:03,740
every four minutes,

175
00:11:04,240 --> 00:11:05,340
you don't even notice

176
00:11:05,340 --> 00:11:06,980
when a train shakes your house.

177
00:11:08,180 --> 00:11:10,780
I was 12 or 13 the first time I noticed.

178
00:11:12,120 --> 00:11:13,900
My friend from school came around

179
00:11:13,900 --> 00:11:14,540
and he said,

180
00:11:15,660 --> 00:11:17,280
damn, your whole house is shaking.

181
00:11:18,720 --> 00:11:20,320
And that was the first time I realised.

182
00:11:22,380 --> 00:11:23,240
What does that mean?

183
00:11:24,440 --> 00:11:26,720
So I was in the bottom bunk

184
00:11:26,720 --> 00:11:27,900
of that bunk bed when I was a kid.

185
00:11:28,780 --> 00:11:30,000
And underneath my bed,

186
00:11:30,260 --> 00:11:31,400
there was a single drawer

187
00:11:31,400 --> 00:11:32,940
that had been removed

188
00:11:32,940 --> 00:11:33,960
from a chest of drawers,

189
00:11:34,480 --> 00:11:36,100
which had probably been destroyed long ago.

190
00:11:37,100 --> 00:11:38,500
And in that single drawer,

191
00:11:38,760 --> 00:11:40,500
I kept all of my worldly possessions.

192
00:11:42,680 --> 00:11:43,400
I'll be honest,

193
00:11:43,480 --> 00:11:45,600
it wasn't a particularly safe house

194
00:11:45,600 --> 00:11:46,240
when I was a kid.

195
00:11:47,340 --> 00:11:48,360
There was danger

196
00:11:48,360 --> 00:11:50,280
and there was violence sometimes.

197
00:11:51,720 --> 00:11:52,760
But, you know,

198
00:11:53,480 --> 00:11:54,020
I was a kid.

199
00:11:54,900 --> 00:11:55,760
What do you do?

200
00:11:57,540 --> 00:11:59,080
And there are a lot of institutions

201
00:11:59,080 --> 00:11:59,940
in our society

202
00:11:59,940 --> 00:12:01,680
that are supposed to protect poor kids

203
00:12:01,680 --> 00:12:02,640
and kids who are not safe.

204
00:12:03,620 --> 00:12:04,420
There's the government,

205
00:12:04,940 --> 00:12:05,840
the welfare state,

206
00:12:06,580 --> 00:12:07,800
charity, philanthropy,

207
00:12:08,360 --> 00:12:09,500
some religious institutions.

208
00:12:09,500 --> 00:12:12,460
All I can tell you is,

209
00:12:12,960 --> 00:12:14,980
I don't remember none of them coming for me.

210
00:12:16,940 --> 00:12:18,240
So, you know,

211
00:12:18,880 --> 00:12:20,120
what do you do?

212
00:12:21,960 --> 00:12:23,160
There wasn't any help

213
00:12:23,160 --> 00:12:24,260
as far as I can remember it

214
00:12:24,260 --> 00:12:24,860
when I was a kid.

215
00:12:25,700 --> 00:12:26,900
But there was a story.

216
00:12:28,540 --> 00:12:30,280
A story is something to hold on to.

217
00:12:31,360 --> 00:12:32,480
You work hard.

218
00:12:33,220 --> 00:12:35,080
You kill all of your exams.

219
00:12:35,080 --> 00:12:37,360
You destroy the competition.

220
00:12:38,540 --> 00:12:39,140
Your friends,

221
00:12:39,700 --> 00:12:40,200
of course.

222
00:12:41,640 --> 00:12:43,100
You beat all your friends

223
00:12:43,100 --> 00:12:44,320
into the top university.

224
00:12:45,460 --> 00:12:46,260
This university.

225
00:12:47,260 --> 00:12:48,319
And then you get

226
00:12:48,319 --> 00:12:49,460
a whole load of new friends.

227
00:12:49,920 --> 00:12:51,780
And you beat those new friends, too,

228
00:12:52,340 --> 00:12:53,280
into the best job.

229
00:12:53,780 --> 00:12:55,000
And then you get the best job

230
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:56,400
working for a bank in the city.

231
00:12:56,400 --> 00:12:59,560
I didn't really know

232
00:12:59,560 --> 00:13:00,000
what that meant,

233
00:13:00,060 --> 00:13:00,480
to be honest.

234
00:13:01,500 --> 00:13:02,660
But I had an image.

235
00:13:03,760 --> 00:13:04,660
It was an image

236
00:13:04,660 --> 00:13:06,400
of a large corner office

237
00:13:06,400 --> 00:13:08,520
high up in a skyscraper somewhere

238
00:13:08,520 --> 00:13:10,400
with carpeted floors

239
00:13:10,400 --> 00:13:11,600
and windows for walls

240
00:13:11,600 --> 00:13:13,900
and a high blue sky

241
00:13:13,900 --> 00:13:14,800
and a warm sun

242
00:13:14,800 --> 00:13:16,199
and views for miles

243
00:13:16,199 --> 00:13:16,980
in every direction.

244
00:13:18,959 --> 00:13:20,240
I don't actually know

245
00:13:20,240 --> 00:13:21,040
if offices like that

246
00:13:21,040 --> 00:13:21,740
really exist.

247
00:13:22,740 --> 00:13:23,939
I never worked in one.

248
00:13:25,319 --> 00:13:25,800
But, you know,

249
00:13:26,400 --> 00:13:27,340
that was a story.

250
00:13:29,280 --> 00:13:30,120
I've got to be honest,

251
00:13:30,220 --> 00:13:31,300
I didn't really work hard.

252
00:13:32,580 --> 00:13:33,400
There wasn't anywhere

253
00:13:33,400 --> 00:13:34,320
to work in my house.

254
